<subSubSection id="33CF848BFFF5FFFDA0B6F95DDE26F8F1" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7B6AD700FFF5FFFDA0B6F95DDE26F8F1" blockId="36.[151,1436,1711,2024]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">
This subspecies was described from Grande 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA2BFF942D9B4F90D" box="[670,760,1712,1736]" name="Comoros" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Comore</collectingCountry>
(Njazidja, 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA35CF942D8A9F90D" box="[893,997,1712,1736]" name="Comoros" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Comoros</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="1F44AAF1FFF5FFFDA3DFF95DDFE7F90D" author="Oberthur" box="[1022,1195,1711,1736]" firstAuthor="Oberthur" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" pagination="177" refId="ref31960" refString="Oberthur, C. (1916) II. - Hesperidae. Observations sur une centurie d'especes de Lepidopteres rhopaloceres malgaches. Etudes de lepidopterologie comparee, par Charles Oberthur, 11, 177 - 244, plates 136 - 137." type="journal article" year="1916">
Oberthür 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA44EF95DDFE7F90D" box="[1135,1195,1711,1736]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="1916.0">1916</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and also occurs on Anjouan (Nzwani, 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA14FF926DA9AF929" box="[366,470,1748,1772]" name="Comoros" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Comoros</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="1F44AAF1FFF5FFFDA1CCF921D939F929" author="Turlin" box="[493,629,1747,1772]" firstAuthor="Turlin" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" pagination="197" refId="ref32982" refString="Turlin, B. (1995) Faune lepidopterique de l'Archipel des Comores (Ocean Indien). (Rhopaloceres, Sphingidae, Attacidae) (6). Lambillionea, 95, 197 - 210." type="journal article" year="1995">
Turlin 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA21DF921D939F929" box="[572,629,1747,1772]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA295F926D85DF929" box="[692,785,1748,1772]" name="Mayotte" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Mayotte</collectingCountry>
(Overseas Department of 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA41DF926DFC6F929" box="[1084,1162,1748,1772]" name="France" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">France</collectingCountry>
) (ABRI collection), and can be expected to occur on other islands of the Comoro archipelago where its food plants occur. ABRI collectors have reared this subspecies many times since 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA2B6F8EED983F8F1" box="[663,719,1820,1844]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="1978.0">1978</number>
from 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF5FFFDA335F8EED8CFF8F1" box="[788,899,1819,1844]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reflexa">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF5FFFDA335F8EED8CFF8F1" box="[788,899,1819,1844]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">D. reflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on Grande 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA427F8EEDF2FF8F1" box="[1030,1123,1820,1844]" name="Comoros" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Comore</collectingCountry>
, Anjouan and 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA524F8EEDE2AF8F1" box="[1285,1382,1820,1844]" name="Mayotte" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Mayotte</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33CF848BFFF5FFFFA0E6F8B2D85AFF11" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="339" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" type="description">
<paragraph id="7B6AD700FFF5FFFCA0E6F8B2D962FED8" blockId="36.[151,1436,1711,2024]" lastBlockId="37.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="338" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">
We also show photographs of caterpillars and a pupa collected on 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF5FFFDA38AF8B2DF56F89D" box="[939,1050,1855,1880]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reflexa">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF5FFFDA38AF8B2DF56F89D" box="[939,1050,1855,1880]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">D. reflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Grande 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF5FFFDA4A0F8B2DF92F89D" box="[1153,1246,1856,1880]" name="Comoros" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">Comore</collectingCountry>
, mostly taken by Alain Gauthier (
<figureCitation id="E3EECB85FFF5FFFDA175F891DA85F8B9" box="[340,457,1891,1916]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1580,1602]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,269,1554]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[151,1436,267,1555]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 34. Early stages of Artitropa erinnys comoranum, collected on Dracaena reflexa, Grande Comore, Comoro Islands; 1 – 4, final instar caterpillar; 5, pupa. 1, 3 – 5, Moroni, 3 – 9 Sep 2014 [© Alain Gauthier]; 2, 13 Apr 2004 [TCEC]. 1, dorsal / dorsolateral view in shelter; 35 mm; 2, detail of head, anterior view; 3, detail of head, anterodorsolateral view; 4, detail of head, anterodorsolateral view; 5, newly formed pupa, dorsolateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253567/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">
Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA188F896DA85F8B9" box="[425,457,1892,1916]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="34.0">34</number>
</figureCitation>
). The head of the final instar caterpillar collected by TCEC (Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA4CFF896DE6DF8B9" box="[1262,1313,1892,1916]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="34.2">34.2</number>
) is yellow brown, with the adfrontals and frons concolorous; just two relatively small black spots on the face on each epicranium, comparable to the form of the caterpillar 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF5FFFDA331F85ED8D1F801" authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1896" box="[784,925,1963,1988]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artitropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="erinnys" subSpecies="ehlersi">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF5FFFDA331F85ED8D1F801" box="[784,925,1963,1988]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="337">A. e. ehlersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Nguru Mountains (Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA53DF85EDE1CF801" box="[1308,1360,1964,1988]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="28.3">28.3</number>
– 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF5FFFDA541F85EDE22F801" box="[1376,1390,1964,1988]" pageId="36" pageNumber="337" value="4.0">4</number>
). In contrast, one caterpillar photographed by Alain Gauthier, has three additional dark dashes dorsally on the adfrontals and frons, comparable to the caterpillar attributed to 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF4FFFCA34BFF6AD8BFFF75" authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1896" box="[874,1011,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artitropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="erinnys" subSpecies="ehlersi">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA34BFF6AD8BFFF75" box="[874,1011,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">A. e. ehlersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingCountry id="03C29790FFF4FFFCA444FF6ADFE2FF75" box="[1125,1198,152,176]" name="Kenya" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Kenya</collectingCountry>
Coast (Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF4FFFCA57AFF6ADEC3FF75" box="[1371,1423,152,176]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" value="28.1">28.1</number>
), while the other has more strongly developed markings on the adfrontals and frons, and lateral spots on the epicranium, comparable to the caterpillars of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF4FFFCA284FF12D87EFF3D" authorityName="Riley" authorityYear="1925" box="[677,818,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artitropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="erinnys" subSpecies="nyasae">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA284FF12D87EFF3D" box="[677,818,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">A. e. nyasae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Ruo Gorge (Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF4FFFCA441FF12DFDFFF3D" box="[1120,1171,224,248]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" value="29.1">29.1</number>
– 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF4FFFCA485FF12DFFEFF3D" box="[1188,1202,224,248]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" value="2.0">2</number>
). The newly formed pupa (Figure 
<number id="CD1DC527FFF4FFFCA10FFEF6DA2CFED8" box="[302,352,260,285]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" value="34.5">34.5</number>
) has no markings.
</paragraph>
<caption id="2FAA8788FFF4FFFCA0B6F90EDADBF8AA" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253566/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" targetBox="[151,1436,361,1739]" targetPageId="37">
<paragraph id="7B6AD700FFF4FFFCA0B6F90EDADBF8AA" blockId="37.[151,1436,1788,1903]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA0B6F90EDA6DF8D7" bold="true" box="[151,289,1788,1810]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">FIGURE 33.</emphasis>
Caterpillar, pupa and adult of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF4FFFCA241F90FD82FF8D6" authority="erinnys" authorityName="erinnys Trimen" authorityYear="1862" box="[608,867,1789,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artitropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="erinnys" subSpecies="erinnys">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA241F90FD82FF8D6" box="[608,867,1789,1811]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Artitropa erinnys erinnys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF4FFFCA3B3F90CDF3BF8D7" authorityName="Bos" authorityYear="1992" baseAuthorityName="Haw." box="[914,1143,1788,1811]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aletriformis">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA3B3F90CDF3BF8D7" box="[914,1143,1788,1811]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Dracaena aletriformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Scotburg, Kwa-Zulu Natal, South Africa [SCC]. 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA14EF8E9DAD9F8F4" bold="true" box="[367,405,1819,1841]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">1–3</emphasis>
, final instar caterpillar: 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA2ADF8E9D9D5F8F4" bold="true" box="[652,665,1819,1841]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">1</emphasis>
, head, anterodorsal view, 26 Sep 2004; 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA413F8E9DF73F8F4" bold="true" box="[1074,1087,1819,1841]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">2</emphasis>
, dorsolateral view; 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA52BF8E9DE5BF8F4" bold="true" box="[1290,1303,1819,1841]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">3</emphasis>
, dorsolateral view. 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA0F4F8C8DBB7F895" bold="true" box="[213,251,1850,1872]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">4–5</emphasis>
, pupa: 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA16DF8C8DA15F895" bold="true" box="[332,345,1850,1872]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">4</emphasis>
, dorsolateral view, 23 Sep 2004; 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA29BF8C8D98AF895" bold="true" box="[698,710,1850,1872]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">5</emphasis>
, lateral view, 23 Sep 2004. 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA3CEF8C8DF59F895" bold="true" box="[1007,1045,1850,1872]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">7–8</emphasis>
, adult female, 26 Sep 2004: 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA567F8C8DE1FF895" bold="true" box="[1350,1363,1850,1872]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">7</emphasis>
, upper surface; 
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF4FFFCA0CCF8ABDBB6F8AA" bold="true" box="[237,250,1881,1903]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">8</emphasis>
, under surface.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="7B6AD700FFF4FFFFA0E6F86ED85AFF11" blockId="37.[151,1436,1947,2008]" lastBlockId="38.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="339" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
We have examined images of just three caterpillars in preparing this account, and they show considerable variation, paralleling that found in different populations in mainland Africa. This highlights the need to understand the extent of individual variation in separate populations and subspecies before coming to firm conclusions about the differences observed in the early stages of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD5AC83FFF7FFFFA2BCFF4ED842FF11" authorityName="Trimen" authorityYear="1862" box="[669,782,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artitropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erinnys">
<emphasis id="49A10B12FFF7FFFFA2BCFF4ED842FF11" box="[669,782,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="339">A. erinnys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
